decessors and colleagues.This volume is the product of a lively conference sponsored by Cornell University, with contributions revised following those interactions. Not everyone sees the development of Indonesian studies in the same way. Yet one senses-and this collection confirms-that disagreements among its practitioners have fostered a vibrant, resilient intellectual community. Contributors discuss photography and the creation of identity, the power of ethnic pop music, cross-border influences on Indonesian contemporary art, violence in the margins, and the shadows inherent in Indonesian literature. These various perspectives illuminate a diverse nation in flux and provide direction for its future exploration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh1 aTagliacozzo, Eric, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501718977423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501718977.jpg  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles